  "prompt": "How do jellyfish breath?",
  "response": "Jellyfish don't have lungs, gills, or a respiratory system like many other animals. Instead, they breathe through a process called **diffusion**. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Thin Body Wall**: Jellyfish have a very thin body wall (only a few cell layers thick). This allows gases to pass easily between their cells and the surrounding water.\n2. **Oxygen Exchange**: Oxygen dissolved in the water diffuses directly through the jellyfish's outer layer into their cells.\n3. **Carbon Dioxide Removal**: Similarly, carbon dioxide, a waste product of cellular respiration, diffuses out of the jellyfish's cells into the surrounding water.\n\nThis simple method of gas exchange works efficiently because jellyfish have a **high surface area-to-volume ratio**, meaning their body structure maximizes contact with the water. Additionally, their slow metabolism requires relatively low amounts of oxygen, making diffusion sufficient for their needs.",
